node.text:
**Sound On** In honor of Mother’s Day, best-selling author and poet Kwame Alexander (@kwamealexander) asked 12 accomplished writers to reflect on how their lives—and their kitchens—mirror their mothers. Everyone got the same prompt, “I am becoming my mother,” and this community poem is a result. Head to the link in our bio to read more about the authors.
Contributors: @vanggarrett, Lesléa Newman, @engle.margarita, @marjorythw, Richard Michelson, Janet Wong, @georgiaheard1, @amstephens_, Maritza Rivera, Reuben Jackson, Lorna Goodison, @erikalsanchez, Deanna Nikaido, and Kwame Alexander

node.title: Kwame Alexander Reads The Ceremony of Giving

node.text:
@welcome.to.chinatown is a grassroots initiative to support Chinatown businesses and amplify community voices that generates much needed momentum to preserve one of New York City’s most vibrant neighborhoods. The folks behind this initiative filmed a very special edition of “Show Me”, our Instagram series that takes a peek into a food lover’s life. Watch the video to see their favorite places to eat, drink, and shop in Manhattan’s Chinatown, and click the link in our bio to learn more about Welcome To Chinatown, including resources on how you can stop Anti-Asian racism happening right now. 🎥: 
@jennyjomeslice

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by bonappetitmag on July 19, 2021. May be an image of dessert.

node.text: Making doughnuts at home is not only possible but fun! And these magnificent, cardamom-cream-filled doughnuts are a great place to start. Breaking cardamom pods in with the pastry cream ingredients will give all other doughnut fillings a run for their money. From getting the dough started to rolling the finished doughnuts in sugar, recipe developer @samanthaseneviratne breaks down the art of making doughnuts from start to finish. Grab the recipe link now in our bio. 📷: @isa.zapata 🍴: @curlygirlcooks 🥣: Nicole Louie

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by bonappetitmag on July 19, 2021. May be an image of food and indoor.

node.text: The key to these juicy grilled chicken breasts? Treating your grill like an oven and dousing the chicken with a tadka-ish sauce. For this recipe, @rachelgurjar blooms whole spices and scallions in oil to maximize their flavor and aroma, then drizzles it over cooled, sliced chicken and greens dressed in a lemony buttermilk dressing. This two-pronged method means perfectly grilled chicken breasts every time (you’re welcome!). Grab the recipe link in our bio. 📷: @emmafishman 🍴: @susietheodorou 🥣: @tripleppp

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by bonappetitmag on July 18, 2021. May be an image of food.

node.text: Dinuguan, the rich Filipino blood stew, has many names. But as a child in Toronto, contributor Yasmin Tayag often heard her relatives call it chocolate meat—a teasing moniker that unsettled her. “Perhaps they felt that jokes like ‘chocolate meat,’ which made light of the differences that made them unique, would ease their entry into a new society,” she writes of the Filipino immigrant experience. Her essay, which traces the dish’s origins from the colonial era all the way to her present, argues to reclaim the term “dinuguan” as a celebration of Philippine creativity, resourcefulness, and defiance. 🎨: @lydia_ortiz

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by bonappetitmag on July 17, 2021. May be an image of strawberry.

node.text: We're calling it: Galatopita (ruffled milk pie) is the must-make summer dessert. This Greek treat calls for scrunching up layers of buttered phyllo, pouring a bath of custard over it, and baking it to crispy-creamy perfection. The end product tastes as dreamy as it looks. “This dessert has so many textural contrasts,” recipe developer @samsanthaeneviratne says, “with crunchy phyllo tops, juicy berries, and creamy custard. Fresh raspberries add a welcome tartness to all the sweetness in the mix.” Grab the recipe link now in our bio. 📷: @emmafishman 🍴: @susietheodorou 🥣: @tripleppp

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by bonappetitmag on July 16, 2021. May be an image of food and indoor.

node.text: Assistant food editor Jessie YuChen (@thelescook) developed a way to grill wings for a crowd that makes it more effortless and foolproof than ever. Baking the wings ahead of time means that there’s no fretting over the grill wondering whether they’re cooked through, and allows you to achieve caramelized perfection with minimal effort. You get an impressive looking dish, a fiery grill show, and easy-breezy-under-control hosting. Read more at the link in our bio. 📷: @emmafishman 🍴: @susietheodorou 🥣: @tripleppp

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by bonappetitmag on July 16, 2021. May be an image of food.

node.text: “The mouthwatering smell of pollo asado brings to mind so many memories of walking from my grandparents’ house to the neighborhood fritanga stand around the corner,” says chef Giovanna Favilli. Giovanna’s pollo asado recipe offers a taste of those childhood memories. A whole chicken gets marinated in a mix of punchy flavors like naranja agria (sour orange) juice and achiote paste. But no worries if you can’t get your hands on sour oranges—Giovanna recommends subbing a mix of orange and lime juice instead. Grab the full recipe in our bio now. 📷: @emmafishman 🍴: Rebecca Jurkevich

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by bonappetitmag on July 15, 2021. May be an image of food.

node.text: “It’s too late! We ruined everything!” @alexandrabeggs cries in her most despairing moments. The oceans are filled with water bottles and corporations don’t give more than a PR hoot about their plastic waste. “But that’s a terrible way to think,” she writes, especially with a new crop of fully compostable kitchen products on the market. Swap out single-use plastics in your kitchen with biodegradable cling wrap, cleaning wipes, and zippered sandwich bags, all at the link in our bio. 📷: @isa.zapata 🍴: @curlygirlcooks 🥣: Nicole Louie

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by bonappetitmag on July 14, 2021. May be an image of food and indoor.

node.text: Consider this recipe a gift to the vegetarians (and just about anyone trying to eat a little less meat) at your next summer cookout. Not only does @rachelgurjar teach us how to get the most out of grilled cauliflower and broccoli; she gives us a bright and minty chutney recipe that’ll play nice with just about anything else you may be cooking these days. This charred vegetable extravaganza becomes the main course with the addition of protein-packed lentils (which you can make a few days in advance). We love that for us. Grab the recipe link in our bio now. 📷: @yudi_ela, 🍴: @susietheodorou 🥣: @tripleppp

node.text: Grilled cheese? Yes, please! But maybe not the kind you’re thinking of. For centuries, South Asian cuisine has featured paneer, a mild non-melting cheese, cooked in high-heat environments like a tandoor. So when we asked associate food editor @rachelgurjar for some meat-free sides to make at the next summer barbecue, she blessed us with a recipe for creamy, spice-rubbed paneer paired with crisp green beans, all charred to perfection on the grill. Delicious is an understatement. Grab the recipe link for Cheesy Charred Green Beans in our bio. 📷: @yudi_ela 🍴: @susietheodorou 🥣: @tripleppp

node.text: Our grilling formula for tender drumsticks with crackly skin includes pineapple, sharp knives, and indirect heat. Associate food editor @rachelgurjar makes deep cuts into drumsticks to ensure her pineapple-and-coconut-cream-forward marinade reaches every nook and cranny of the chicken. After a quick soak (just 15 minutes!), the drumsticks are grilled over indirect heat to cook through, then thrown onto the flames for a perfectly crispy and charred finish. Grab the recipe link now in our bio. 📷: @emmafishman 🍴: @susietheodorou 🥣: @tripleppp

node.text: Yes, a cheese slicer is great for slicing cheese, but why stop there? Writer @meganjzhang sure doesn't. She uses her Scandinavian ostehøvel—invented in 1925 by a Norwegian carpenter who longed to plane his blocks of Jarlsberg—to evenly slice potatoes for the air fryer, kiwis and mangoes for fruit tarts, and boiled eggs for toast. "The slices are always shipshape, and I’ve never accidentally cut myself. Can any of us say the same about a knife?" More on Megan's favorite kitchen tool at the link in our bio. 📷: @emmafishman
